    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
            <p>Not published before <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>124200</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested" key=""><name nymRef="#Πράταρχος"><supplied reason="lost">Πρ</supplied>άταρχ<supplied reason="lost">ος</supplied></name>
                    <lb n="2"/><persName type="attested" key=""><name type="patronymic" nymRef="#Κάρνις"><supplied reason="lost">Κ</supplied>άρνι<supplied reason="lost">ος</supplied></name></persName></persName>
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Pratarkhos fils de Karnis.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="en" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Pratarchos son of Karnis.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="it" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Pratarchos figlio di Karnis.</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
               <p>The low inventory number corresponds to the items found before World War II, moved to Tripolitania during the war and rearranged after 
               1953 when Goodchild was controller at Cyrene.</p>
                <p>Both names are already attested in Cyrenaica. Karnis is especially Cyrenaican (see <bibl><ptr target="#robert1967"/></bibl>).</p>
	<p/>
	<p/>
            </div></body>
